\par XVn ADR has of \'d2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935 INT TRN0}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 \'d3 to \'d2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935 INT TRN9}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f37\insrsid3036935 \'d3 for the K144XV. Band-data 
\par outputs are set accordingly. This may be useful when the K144XV is
\par used as an IF for higher-band external transverters. (If you have a 
\par K144XV, the original }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935 INT TRN1}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935  will now be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935 INT TRN0}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f37\insrsid3036935  in the menu.
\par This is the new recommended setting if you\rquote re not using external
\par transverters in conjunction with the K144XV.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935 NOTE:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935  When using the K144XV, XVn RF can be set to the RF band 
\par of an external transverter that is using the K144XV as an I.F., rather
\par than at the 2-meter band edge (144).
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\cf2\insrsid3036935 MCU 4.06 / DSP 2.60, 8-19-2010
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 
\par * DVR PLAY/RECORD FIX: The AF PLAY and AF REC positions 
\par within the DVR\rquote s 90-second audio loop were not being setup correctly. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\cf2\insrsid3036935 MCU 4.05 / DSP 2.60, 7-20-2010
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 * Additional K3->P3 command responses, including BN.
\par This release required for production P3 users.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\cf2\insrsid3036935 
\par MCU 4.03 / DSP 2.60, 6-10-2010
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 
\par * 75 BAUD (100 WPM) RTTY SUPPORT: The internal data
\par encoder/decoder now supports both 45 and 75 baud. To 
\par select the desired rate, use the DATA MD switch, then rotate
\par VFO A.
\par 
\par * ULTRA-FAST BREAK-IN AND QRQ CW (\'d2CW+\'d3):  
\par If you set CONFIG:CW QRQ to ON in the menu, the K3 will 
\par provide extremely fast break-in at all CW speeds. It will also
\par allow both the internal keyer and external keying to work
\par at up to 100 WPM. (Be sure to turn on both QSK and VOX.) 
\par The \'d2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935 +}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 \'d3 mode icon turns on when }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935 CW+}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f37\insrsid3036935  is in effect. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935 Tip:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935  You may want to assign the CW QRQ menu entry to 
\par a programmable switch function (e.g., PF1) for quick access.
\par This can be done by locating the CW QRQ menu entry, then
\par holding PF1 until you see \'d2PF1 SET\'d3.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935 Note 1:  There are limitations to QRQ CW mode at present. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 You cannot use SHIFT, or turn on RIT, XIT, or {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}SPLIT{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. However,
\par you can still use splits, in effect, if you have the sub receiver
\par installed: Turn the SUB on, and use VFO B as the receive VFO. 
\par (In a subsequent firmware release, RIT/XIT will be usable over
\par a small range in QRQ mode.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935 Note 2:  If you use CONFIG:TX DLY}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935  to set external keying
\par delay, you may need to adjust its setting for QRQ CW use. Also,
\par any increase in the default (8 ms) may decrease the maximum
\par available CW speed.
\par 
\par * AF BALANCE CONTROL IMPROVED: The SUB AF control
\par can be used as a main/sub RX balance control (see CONFIG:
\par SUB AF). Previously, when the control was rotated fully 
\par clockwise, main receiver audio would not be fully turned off. 
\par This has been corrected.
\par 
\par * ADDED ERROR CODE \'d2ERR RXF\'d3. This message is flashed 
\par if you switch to a crystal filter that is too wide for the present 
\par settings. For example, ERR RXF will flash if you are in QRQ 
\par CW mode and select a filter wider than 2.8 kHz. To correct this,
\par you'll need to turn off wider-bandwidth crystal filters either 
\par manually (using CONFIG:{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}FLx{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}ON{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}) or via K3 Utility.
\par 
\par * FIXED FSK-D STUCK TONE: Occasionally, sending RTTY
\par using the keyer paddle (FSK-D) would leave sidetone on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\cf2\insrsid3036935 
\par MCU 3.97 / DSP 2.58, 5-9-2010
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 
\par * TX INHIBIT IMPROVEMENT: If TX INH is active (see 
\par CONFIG:TX INH), voice monitor and CW/DATA tones are disabled,
\par giving the operator audible feedback about inhibited status to 
\par supplement the flashing \'d2TX\'d3 icon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\cf2\insrsid3036935 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 * DSP NOISE BLANKER IMPROVED: A new algorithm has
\par been added that makes the DSP NB more effective on
\par some types of noise. Odd-numbered {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}DSP{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}NB
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} levels (t1-1, 
\par t1-3, t1-5, etc.) apply the new algorithm, while even-numbered 
\par levels use the original. To avoid unwanted interaction between
\par the NB and on-air signals, always use the lowest effective setting.
\par 
\par * CW KEYING ARTIFACT WITH AFX/DELAY ELIMINATED:
\par The \'d2DELAY\'d3 settings of AFX previously created a small audio
\par artifact when listening to CW keying in the presence of background 
\par noise or signals.
\par 
\par * AGC-OFF S-METER IMPROVEMENT: Turning AGC off no longer
\par results in a drop in the S-meter reading. This was most noticeable
\par in the presence of strong band noise. 
\par 
\par * K144XV S-METER NOW ACCURATE: The S-meter reading is
\par is now adjusted to account for RX gain when the K144XV is in use.
\par 
\par * TX NOISE GATE IMPROVED: The voice transmit noise gate
\par now uses a downward expander rather than simple gating.
\par See TX GATE menu entry for further details.
\par 
\par * MANUAL NOTCH: Pitch now defaults to 1000 rather than 2000 Hz.
\par This starting point is a better compromise between CW and SSB.
\par 
\par * ESSB ON/OFF COMMAND: The new \'d2ES\'d3 control command
\par can be used to turn ESSB on/off via a switch macro or from a
\par software application. The K3 must also be in LSB or USB mode
\par before {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}ESSB{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}ON{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} takes effect. (See K3 Programmer\rquote s Reference.)
\par 
\par * BN REMOTE CONTROL COMMAND (BAND CHANGE):
\par Previously this command was \'d2GET only\'d3, returning the 
\par present band number (00-24). It can now be used as a SET
\par command to switch to the desired band. For example, BN00;
\par switches to the last-used frequency on 160 m. Note: VFO B 
\par will also be restored to its last frequency used on the new band,
\par except in the case where CONFIG:{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}VFO{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}IND
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} is set to YES. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\cf2\insrsid3036935 MCU 3.94 / DSP 2.54, 4-17-2010
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935 K3 Memory Editor:\line }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 
\par * This revision of K3 firmware works with our new K3 Memory 
\par Editor (presently PC/Windows-only, but may eventually work on other
\par platforms). The memory editor allows you to edit frequency
\par memories 00-99 and, if desired, per-band quick memories (M1-M4).
\par Each memory includes a \'d2QSY\'d3 button, providing convenient 
\par memory selection. Memory contents can be saved in a file
\par and shared with other K3 users. (Further details posted elsewhere.)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 * MEMORY CHANNEL COMMAND (MC): This new remote-control
\par command was created in support of the K3 Memory Editor (see
\par above). Sending an MC command to the K3 loads VFOs from a 
\par memory (or \'d2channel\'d3), emulating M>V. It can be used in switch 
\par macros. Examples: \'d2MC080;\'d3 loads memory #80. \'d2MC100;\'d3 loads 
\par 160-m quick-memory M1. (For details on creating macros, 
\par refer to K3 Utility Help or the K3 Programmer\rquote s Reference.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935 Other New Features:\line }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 \line * SEPARATE RECEIVE EQ FOR CW MODE: To set up CW RX EQ, 
\par select CW mode, then use {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}MAIN{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}:RX EQ. To set up voice-mode RX EQ, 
\par select any non-CW mode. (Mode can be changed while in the menu.)
\par 
\par * SEPARATE TRANSMIT EQ FOR SSB MODE:  The SSB transmit 
\par passband can now be set up differently from AM/FM/ESSB. To set up 
\par SSB TX EQ, select USB or LSB with ESSB }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\insrsid3036935 off}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 , then use {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}MAIN
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}:TX EQ. 
\par To set up AM/FM/ESSB TX EQ, select AM, FM, or USB/LSB with 
\par ESSB }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\insrsid3036935 on}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 .  (To turn ESSB on/off, tap \lquote 1\rquote  in CONFIG:TX ESSB. When  
\par ON ,the \'d2+\'d3 mode icon appears.)  Also see TE}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 command, below.
\par 
\par * TRANSMIT EQ SETUP COMMAND (TE): Can be used 
\par in switch macros to quickly optimize TX EQ settings for different 
\par users or mics. For example, \'d2TE-08+00+00+00+00+00+00+00;\'d3 
\par cuts the 50-Hz EQ band by 8 dB.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 * Full support for P3 Panadapter. Allows very fast K3-to-P3 response
\par during VFO movement, etc.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\insrsid3036935 
\par For software developers:\line 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\insrsid3036935 * See TE and MC commands, above.
