\par Details appear below.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\fs22\insrsid3036935 New Feature: Band {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Independence{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 for the Sub Receiver
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\fs22\cf2\insrsid3036935 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\fs22\insrsid3036935 * MAIN/SUB RECEIVER BAND {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}INDEPENDENCE{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. If CONFIG:VFO {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}IND{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} 
\par is set to YES, then VFO A and B can be set to different bands. In this case
\par BAND UP/BAND DN will only move VFO A, but in BSET mode, they will apply
\par to VFO B. VFO B can also have a different mode from VFO A. Some RX
\par parameters can be set differently for the sub receiver when in BSET mode,
\par including PRE, ATTN, all DSP controls, and NB (noise blanker) settings.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\fs22\insrsid3036935 Limitations:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\fs22\insrsid3036935  For now, NR, notch, and some other controls remain common 
\par to both receivers. Internal text decode (CW, FSK-D, PSK-D) is available 
\par only for the main receiver. Scanning still must be set up using both VFO A 
\par and B on the same band. Memory recall only updates VFO A if VFO B is
\par on a different band. (Most restrictions will be removed in future revisions.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\fs22\insrsid3036935 New AGC Features
\par 
\par Introduction:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\fs22\insrsid3036935  All AGC systems modulate in-band signals to some degree, 
\par creating IMD if multiple signals are present. But you now have several choices 
\par when conditions are difficult: (1) AGC OFF, which eliminates virtually all 
\par in-band IMD, but requires \'d2riding\'d3 of the RF GAIN control. (2) Slow AGC 
\par (AGC-S) with a nonzero hold time, typically 0.2 seconds or more (see}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\fs22\insrsid3036935  
\par CONFIG:AGC HLD }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\fs22\insrsid3036935 below). This is nearly as clean as AGC OFF, but the AGC 
\par will charge on strong signals, reducing gain for the duration of the AGC HLD
\par amount. This can be distracting. (3) Soft-decay AGC (see}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\fs22\insrsid3036935  CONFIG:AGC DCY}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\fs22\insrsid3036935 ,
\par below, which applies to AGC-S/-F). This recovers much faster than AGC-S with 
\par a long hold applied, and produces only a little more IMD. In the case of AGC-F 
\par (fast), soft decay will result in slower recovery time between code elements
\par than normal decay (nor), but it will still be much faster than AGC-S with a
\par hold time applied. (4) Normal-decay AGC. This is the traditional DSP-based
\par AGC decay characteristic, and it will create a lot more IMD than the 
\par other alternatives. (An application note showing the effect on actual signals
\par is pending.)
\par 
\par * AGC DCY MENU ENTRY (AGC decay type): Allows you to select "Soft" 
\par or normal AGC decay characteristic. When AGC DCY is set to \'d2Soft,\'d3 both 
\par slow and fast AGC will create less in-band IMD (intermodulation distortion)
\par in multi-signal situations (e.g., pileups). You can assign AGC DCY to a
\par programmable function switch (PF1/2 hold, or M1-4 tap or hold) if you
\par need to turn it on/off quickly.
\par 
\par * AGC HLD MENU ENTRY (slow AGC hold time): AGC HLD now
\par applies to CW mode (originally it applied only to voice/data). AGC HLD 
\par may reduce receive IMD caused by normal AGC-S/AGC-F decay times.
\par Settings of about 0.3-1.0 seconds should improve copy when many 
\par closely spaced signals are present, as in a CW pileup. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f37\fs22\insrsid3036935 No effect on 
\par AGC-F}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\fs22\insrsid3036935 .
